The diffraction peak corresponding to the lattice planes (111), (200), and (220) were used for calculation because these peaks are well resolved and do not show any interferences (Fig. 1f and Table S3). The average crystallite size gives a value of 6 nm, it being similar to that observed by TEM.
The three peaks at 2θ values of 43.4, 50.5, and 74.2° corresponding to (111), (200), and (220) planes of copper were compared with the standard diffraction card of Joint Committee on Powder Diffraction Standards (JCPDS), copper file No. 04–0836 (Supplementary material, Table S3) [46].
Small diffraction peaks located at 42.3° and 61.4° were assigned to the planes (200) and (220) distinctive of Cu2O nanoparticles (Fig. 1f). The presence of Cu2O indicates the partial oxidation of copper nanoparticles with dissolved oxygen in the solution during the drying process [47]. According to Khalid et al. [48], copper nanoparticles combined with the oxygen present in the ambient atmosphere forms an oxide layer on the particle surface when exposed to air.
